result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

The defendant Brian J Robinson was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Possession of THC, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.41(3g)(e).
  • Possess Drug Paraphernalia, an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 961.573(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

superAgency.notes: If Defendant satisfies conditions, State will move to dismiss Count 1.

miscConds.notes: Maintain full time work, school, or combination of the two. Complete high school or obtain a GED/HSED.

Commit no further criminal acts during the period of this agreement. Have no contact with anyone involved in the illegal use or sale of controlled substances. The defendant understands that " no contact" means no direct or indirect contact, whether in person, by phone, or by mail, and whether initiated by the defendant or by someone on the defendant's behalf. Consume no alcohol beverages or controlled substances. No entry into bars or taverns. Not to possess drug paraphernalia. Defendant will not drive any motor vehicle unless or until his/her license has been reinstated.

Take any/all medicines prescribed to the defendant by a licensed physician. Defendant shall comply with any and all rules of probation and successfully complete any term of probation ordered as a part of this case.   Defendant shall provide a copy of this agreement, along with the Criminal Complaint, to any counselor and sign any and all releases necessary to allow the counselor (or agency) to report compliance or lack thereof to the District Attorney's Office. Any assessments done without this agreement and the Criminal Complaint(s) being supplied to the counselor will be considered violations of this agreement and not be accepted.  This agreement may be revoked or the defendant may have to complete a new assessment.

Complete an Alcohol and/or Other Drug Abuse (AODA) Assessment with a certified Alcohol and Drug Abuse Counselor, at an appropriate counseling or treatment center and willingly cooperate in any recommended counseling or treatment. The defendant must ensure that the counselor sends the written results of said assessment to the District Attorney's Office on or before November 1, 2016. If counseling is recommended, the defendant must ensure that the counselor sends written documentation of the defendant's attendance and compliance with any recommendation to the District Attorney's Office by August 1, 2017.
$100 fine plus costs. Paid in full.
Not to possess or consume any controlled substances without a valid prescription and then only take in the amount and frequency prescribed.
Complete any counseling, evaluations, programs and assessments as appropriate resulting from the Department's COMPAS assessment. Submit DNA sample.
Obtain AODA assessment and comply with treatment recommendations.
